	abstract = {This paper reviews the LiDAR technology and available system with wide application areas (particularly in tropical forest ecosystem studies) along with the basic principles of this tool. In forest applications LiDAR systems can be classified based on the following characteristics: (i) the ability to record the range to the first return and/or multiple return or fully recording the return waveform; (ii) diameter of footprint (small footprint system - few centimetres in diameter, and large footprint system - metres in diameter); and (iii) the potential sampling rate and scanning pattern. Also presented is an overview of specifications of available LiDAR systems including Laser Vegetation Imaging Sensor, Scanning LiDAR Imager of canopies by echo recovery, Shuttle 1/2, and Vegetation Canopy LiDAR. Major applications of LiDAR system are in the assessment of Digital elevation Model, bathymetric measurements, in forestry, coastal management, facility management, wetlands, floodplain and glacier/ice sheet mapping, in disaster response and damage assessment, and in urban modelling. Finally, the importance of LiDAR remote sensing in forest inventories is also discussed.},
